value.0: "Thank you. This might just save my life some day, if the hunters return. I hope you like the boots. Was there anything else?"
His head jerks around nervously to make certain that none of his other guests can overhear, then he leans in and whispers conspiratorily.
"She wants me to tell you about it? I guess you have a right to know, if anybody does. But take care, this information has cost one person her life already."
"Several years ago, the keep was hit with a storm of the likes not seen in over a century. While the storm raged, a carriage came up to the keep and demanded entrance."
"A dark and frightening footman opened the carriage and a beautiful and elegantly dressed lady stepped out and came into my inn."
"On the contrary, when one beheld her all cares were cast away and troubles became entirely insignificant."
"Her face was enchanting; it drew every eye and held it. She moved with such elegant grace, it was like watching a cat strut across a room like she owned everything."
"She paid for my most expensive room and told me she would be staying for at least a week. When she retired for the night, the only subject of conversation was the mysterious beauty."
"But she never gave me a name. She asked me to simply call her milady. I thought it was odd, but who was I to argue with such beauty... and such gold. She was rich and willing to share."
"The lady stayed in her room for several days, and the storm raged on the entire time. She would order food from the maid that I provided her."
"Patience. I will get there. The lady stayed in her room for several days, and the storm raged on the entire time. She would order food from the maid that I provided her."
"I know the serving girl was receiving gold from the lady, but over the course of several days, the girl began to become skittish."
"I asked her what was wrong, but every time she went to speak, the words stuck in her throat."

"Exactly. I became concerned, so I found a way to eavesdrop on the lady's room, from in the attic. At first I could hear chanting and mumbling, but then I noticed that it was just a repetition of a single phrase."
"She was saying, 'Come north, come north, follow the rumors, come north. Hear me <FirstName>. Follow the Masked man. Come to your new home."
"I had never heard your name, so all I knew was that this woman was using magic to call someone."
"Why would I do such a thing. I have nothing against you and nothing to gain from such a lie."
"The lady left shortly thereafter. I neither saw nor heard from her ever again, but I believe that she must have returned, or sent someone here."
"About a month later, the maid was down in the market square, gossiping about the lady, when suddenly she went pale, stopped speaking and walked away."
"Her corpse was found in a back alley, mangled and partially eaten. I wondered if there was a connection, so I went to Yenna, for she is the most powerful person in the keep."
"It was the look on my maid's face. It was the same look that she had when she worked for the lady. My instincts are very sharp when it comes to observing people, and I know it was related."
"I suspect that you shall discover more as you get to know the residents of the keep. But whatever this person is, be very careful. She obviously has some power over your mind."
"Good luck, <FirstName>. I hope you can overcome your adversaries and live a long life."
"Never. I would tell no one, for even if they believed me, what could anyone else do? Yenna is very powerful. I knew she would grasp the connection better than anyone."
"What could he do? I was every bit as capable as him and Yenna was stronger than us both."
"Obviously. Yenna contacted me and told me not to tell anyone, unless she sent them to me. I suspect that there is someone living in the keep who knows this lady."
"And so we came north at your insistence, though none of the rest of us ever heard these rumors. What can this mean?"
"This does explain your single-minded drive to hunt such a powerful creature, <FirstName>."
"That is why you chased the Masked Man even when Trip gives you sensible advice, <FirstName>! You had a voice in your head, just like me!"
"<FirstName>, that is why you kept pressing us to chase down the Masked Man, even when we tried to argue with you."
"We only have a few rooms left, though they are nice ones. It costs 30 gold per week, and I will take the first 30 right up front."
" With all the landowners forced to stay in the keep, business has been plentiful. Are you interested?"
"If you should change your mind, I would be more than happy to offer you a room. Was there anything else you needed?"
